                <div type="title" xml:lang="en">
                    <head>
                        <lb/><orig>Embleme</orig> 35. Of the Secrets of Nature.
                        <lb/>As Ceres accustomed Triptolemus, and Thetis Achilles to abide in
                        <lb/>fire, <choice><orig>soe</orig><reg>so</reg></choice> <orig>allso</orig> <orig>doth</orig> an artist the stone.
                    </head>
                </div>
                
                
                <div type="epigram" xml:lang="en">
                    <head><orig>Epigramme</orig> 35.</head>
                    <lg>
                        <l>Achilles and Triptolemus <choice><orig>enur'd</orig><reg>inured</reg></choice>,</l>
                        <l>By documents, the hottest flames <choice><orig>endur'd</orig><reg>endured</reg></choice>:</l>
                        <l>Thetis and Ceres thus did them <orig>sustaine</orig>,</l>
                        <l>By night with fire, <choice><orig>ith'</orig><reg>in the</reg></choice> day with <orig>milke</orig> amaine.</l>
                        <l>As to a babe the breast is <orig>naturall</orig>,</l>
                        <l><orig>Soe</orig> fire to <choice><orig>th'</orig><reg>the</reg></choice> <choice><orig>med'cine</orig><reg>medicine</reg></choice> <orig>Philosophicall</orig>.</l>
                    </lg>
                </div>
                
                
                <pb n="111"/> <!-- Change to page number of the actual manuscript -->
                <div type="discourse" xml:lang="en">
                    <head>Discourse 35.</head>
                    <ab><!--Our convention will be that if we have break = "no" then it means that the word is broken across the line with a dash--> 
                        <lb/>Lycurgus that Law=maker of the Spartans <orig>Shewed</orig> to the people in<pc>-</pc><milestone unit="section" n="e03-01" /> <!-- Change the value of n to "e" plus the number of the emblem (in two digits), followed by a hyphen and then a two-digit count of sentence -->
                        <lb/>an assembly in the Theater by an ocular example, how <orig>farre</orig> <orig>custome</orig>
                        <lb/>and use whether good or <orig>evill</orig> may <orig>prævayle</orig>, <orig>hee</orig> bringing in two whelps
                        <lb/>produced at one litter, and between both setting a <choice><orig>pott</orig><reg>pot</reg></choice> full of meat,<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>and a hare, one of which whelps seeing the food and the hare, left
                        <lb/>the food and <choice><orig>pursud</orig><reg>pursued</reg></choice> the hare, because <orig>hee</orig> was <choice><orig>soe</orig><reg>so</reg></choice> accustomed, but
                        <lb/>the other not regarding the hare, emptyed the <choice><orig>pott</orig><reg>pot</reg></choice>, <orig>hee</orig> being <orig>allso</orig><pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>soe</orig> accustomed: which being done, behold, <orig>sayth</orig> <orig>hee</orig>, here you see by
                        <lb/>little ones, how <orig>farre</orig> education and <orig>custome</orig> may <orig>prævayle</orig>, even in those,
                        <lb/>which nature <orig>hath</orig> produced exactly alike, and of the same litter: After
                        <lb/>this manner therefore is it convenient to rectify or direct nature to bet
                        <lb break="no"/>ter things, which is as wax, easily flexible to vice or virtue. That<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>which <orig>hee</orig> <orig>hath</orig> demonstrated to be true in <choice><orig>politicks</orig><reg>politics</reg></choice>, the Philosophers
                        <lb/><orig>doe</orig> agree to be <orig>allso</orig> <choice><orig>soe</orig><reg>so</reg></choice> in <choice><orig>Physicks</orig><reg>Physics</reg></choice>. How <orig>effectuall</orig> <orig>custome</orig> is in<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>men and brutes daily examples are seen throughout the whole world,
                        <lb/>in vegetables <orig>allso</orig> are many obvious, but in <orig>minerall</orig> and <orig>metallicke</orig><pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>bodyes</orig> <orig>wee</orig> have not <choice><orig>soe</orig><reg>so</reg></choice> much experience: yet <orig>neverthelesse</orig> they fix
                        <lb/>their stone by <orig>custome</orig> in fire <orig>agreable</orig> to it, as they in innumerable<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>places <orig>doe</orig> signify: For it must be nourished by fire, as a child by <orig>milke</orig>
                        <lb/>upon its mothers breasts: whereupon <orig>sayth</orig> Emiganus; behold the babe<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>sucking, and hinder him not: And Bodillus, The infant <orig>borne</orig> is nou
                        <lb break="no"/>rished by <orig>milke</orig> and fire alone, and by little and little whilst <orig>hee</orig>
                        <lb/>is very young, and the more <orig>hee</orig> is burned, his bones being comforted,
                        <lb/><orig>hee</orig> is brought to youth, to which attaining, <orig>hee</orig> is able to provide for<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>himselfe</orig>: And Arnold in the Rosary booke 2. Chapt 7. Yet the Medicine
                        <lb/>must be a long time roasted by fire, and nourished as a child<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>with the breasts. These same things have the most ancient Philo
                        <lb break="no"/>sophers been pleased to demonstrate by the <choice><orig>allegoryes</orig><reg>allegories</reg></choice> of Triptole
                        <lb break="no"/>mus and Achilles accustomed to <orig>lye</orig> and being hardened in fire, they
                        <lb/>both denoting nothing <orig>els</orig> but the <orig>Chymicall</orig> subject, besides which
                        <lb/>the fable would be insignificant and absurd, unworthy either to be
                        <lb/>appropriated to other <orig>morall</orig> things, or inculcated to the ears of the<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>learned: Ceres did as a <orig>Nurce</orig> feed Triptolemus in the day time<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>with <orig>milke</orig>, and in the night <orig>layd</orig> him in fire, whereupon the<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>youth being very well nourished, his father Eleusius at length<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>tooke</orig> notice of it: hereupon Ceres <orig>killd</orig> Eleusius, and gave the<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>youth Triptolemus a <choice><orig>chariott</orig><reg>chariot</reg></choice> <orig>drawne</orig> with winged Dragons,<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>whereby <orig>hee</orig> <orig>passd</orig> through the <orig>aire</orig> into all parts of the world,<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>and taught men how to sow <orig>corne</orig>: But this Triptolemus is the<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>tincture nourished by fire after a <orig>Philosophicall</orig> manner, which
                        <lb/>being <orig>drawne</orig> by Serpents, that is, Mercury, taught men how the
                        
                        
                        
                        <pb n="112"/><fw>Discourse 3.</fw><!-- Page number of the actual manuscript, followed by the header on the page. -->
                        <lb/>Philosophers seeds are to be cast into their earth. These same things
                        <lb/>are ascribed to Osiris, who to tha end <orig>tooke</orig> a view of the whole world,
                        <lb/>as <orig>wee</orig> have <orig>elswhere</orig> demonstrated, and to Dionysius, who travelled<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>throughout the world teaching men the use of wine: Now these three
                        <lb/>Triptolemus, Osiris, and Dionysius are of one intention and office,<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>yea one thing; as <orig>allso</orig> Achilles, who being most valiant was to be<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>sent to the Trojane <orig>warre</orig>; his father was Peleus, that is, earth, or the
                        <lb/><orig>mountaine</orig> Peleus, his mother Thetis <orig>goddesse</orig> of the Sea or waters; from
                        <lb/>these Achilles descended: But at their <choice><orig>nuptialls</orig><reg>nuptials</reg></choice> the golden apple of Eris
                        <lb/>was produced, the first cause of the <choice><orig>Trojane</orig><reg>Trojan</reg></choice> <orig>warre</orig>, wherefore <orig>pro
                        <lb break="no"/>ceding</orig> from those <choice><orig>nuptialls</orig><reg>nuptials</reg></choice> reason there was that <orig>hee</orig> should determine
                        <lb/>it: Achilles is <orig>sayd</orig> to be hardened by his mother after the same manner<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>as the <orig>aforesayd</orig> Triptolemus by Ceres, concerning <orig>whome</orig> <orig>wee</orig> have
                        <lb/><orig>sayd</orig> enough in the 6th <orig>booke</orig> of <choice><orig>Hieroglyphicks</orig><reg>Hieroglyphics</reg></choice>, which here to repeat<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>wee</orig> <orig>thinke</orig> superfluous. The nutriment therefore of the Stone is fire,
                        <lb/>but it is not thereby (as some may falsely imagine) extended into lon
                        <lb break="no"/>gitude, latitude, and profundity, nor <orig>doth</orig> it receive increment in<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>weight; because it acquires <orig>onely</orig> virtue, maturation, and <orig>colour</orig> from
                        <lb/>fire, carrying all the rest with it as <choice><orig>viaticke</orig><reg>viatics</reg></choice> provisions: For when its<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>parts are from <orig>severall</orig> places congested, purged, and <orig>conjoyned</orig>, it <orig>hath</orig> in
                        <lb/>it all things requisite for it: Whereupon <orig>sayth</orig> a Philosopher in the Ro
                        <lb break="no"/>sary. Omnia fert Secum quibus indiget hæc aqua fætum.
                        <lb/>Nor indeed is any strange thing added to it from the beginning to the
                        <lb/>end, except it be homogeneous, nor separated, if not heterogeneous:<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>But every man ought to consider, before <orig>hee</orig> begin any thing, how <orig>hee</orig>
                        <lb/>may come to the knowledge of those Dragons that are to be <orig>joyned</orig> to
                        <lb/>the chariot of Triptolemus, which are winged and volatile, which
                        <lb/>if you desire to know, you will find them in the <orig>Philosophicall</orig> dung:<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>for they are dung, and are generated from dung, and are that <orig>vessell</orig>,
                        <lb/>which Mary <orig>sayth</orig>, is not <choice><orig>negromanticall</orig><reg>negromantical</reg></choice>, but the regiment of your
                        <lb/>fire, without which you will effect nothing: I have revealed to you<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>the truth, which by incredible pains I acquired from the monuments
                        <lb/>of the Ancients, not without the expense of many years<pc>. . . .</pc>
                    </ab>   
                </div>
                
